maskl(i) returns an integer with the leftmost i bits set to 1.
maskr(i) returns an integer with the rightmost i bits set to 1.

bit_size(0) = 32
full mask   = -1

i = 0
  maskl(i) = 0
  maskr(i) = 0

i = 1
  maskl(i) = -2147483648
  maskr(i) = 1

i = 2
  maskl(i) = -1073741824
  maskr(i) = 3

i = 4
  maskl(i) = -268435456
  maskr(i) = 15

i = 8
  maskl(i) = -16777216
  maskr(i) = 255

i = 32
  maskl(i) = -1
  maskr(i) = -1

using masks with iand:
iand(15, maskr(1)) = 1
iand(15, maskr(2)) = 3
iand(15, maskr(3)) = 7
iand(15, maskr(4)) = 15

left-mask examples depend on the integer bit size:
maskl(1) = -2147483648
maskl(2) = -1073741824
maskl(3) = -536870912
maskl(4) = -268435456
